description.value: A heavy jar-stopper made of red siltware pottery. The fabric contains grit and voids from burned-out chaff. The top is convex and has been roughly smoothed. On the underside there is an integral projecting boss of hemispherical shape, designed to fit the mouth of a vessel. All the lower part was made as a unit, expanding from the boss to a wide flange with an incurved edge. The hollow interior was sealed by adding more clay to bridge the top. The seam of this closure lies about 2cm from the perimeter of the object. The incised mark on the side is Petrie’s Findspot number.

description.value: Fragment of a large lid of a stone vessel made of white limestone, broken into two fragments and glued. Parts of the lid are broken off. The upper and underside are flat and well smoothed, the lip is 1.1 cm wider on both sides than the base, with a well defined ridge. The top is decorated with a floral depiction drawn in black lines. The centre consists of a circle from which the leaves span out. The outlines of the leaves were filled in by a substance that is now recognisable as a lighter whitish colour than the background. It seems that the lid was reused as it was cut into halves in a straight line while the circular outer edge shows notches on the upper and lower side in an irregular pattern around the object, probably wear marks from strings for the reuse as a weight or tool.
